&lt;p&gt;You can transfer JSON encoded HTML newlines like this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$return['message'] = 'First Entry: ' . $_POST['Name1'] . '&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt; '  . 'Second Entry: ' .    $_POST['Name2'] . '&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt; ' . 'Third Entry: ' . $_POST['Name3'];  
echo json_encode($return);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Or convert newlines (
) into newline tags. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The nicer way though would be to leave that kind of processing to the client by e.g. returning an array of messages:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$return['message'] = array();
$return['message'][] = 'First Entry: ' . $_POST['Name1'];
$return['message'][] = 'Second Entry: ' . $_POST['Name2'];
$return['message'][] = 'Third Entry: ' . $_POST['Name3'];
echo json_encode($return);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And leave the processing to the client (maybe the client wants the messages wrapped in a paragraph tag later on):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;function(data)
{
    $('&amp;lt;div id="output2"&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;').insertAfter($('#agreement-information'));
    $('#output2').html(data.message.join('&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt;')).show(500);
    $('#ouput2').append(data);  
}
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

